  "text": "You have a preview view of this article while we are checking your access. When we have confirmed access, the full article content will load.12 Days That Changed Syria: The Rebel Offensive in VisualsCredit...Daniel Berehulak/The New York Times12 Days That Changed Syria: The Rebel Offensive in VisualsCredit...Daniel Berehulak/The New York TimesDec. 10, 2024In just two weeks, rebel forces tore across Syria, shattering the stalemate left by more than a decade of civil war and bringing an end to more than five decades of brutal rule by the Assad dynasty.The pace of the advance was as dizzying as its implications.Here’s how it unfolded in photos, videos and maps:NOV. 27The offensive beginsThe first thrust was sudden.For years, the Islamist group Hayat Tahrir al-Sham consolidated control in its stronghold in Idlib in Syria’s northwest. Then on Nov. 27, the rebels suddenly began a rapid push east toward Aleppo, a major city that suffered some of the most brutal and protracted fighting during the country’s long civil war.ImageRebel fighters outside Atarib, western Aleppo Province, Nov. 27.Credit...Abdulaziz Ketaz/Agence France-Presse — Getty ImagesOn Nov. 27, the rebels announced a striking initial success: They had overrun a Syrian government base, captured soldiers, taken tanks and seized several villages. “In a matter of about 10 hours,” an analyst told The Times that day, the rebels were within a few miles of Aleppo.VideoRebel fighters drove through Al-Talhiya, Syria, as they advanced toward Aleppo on Nov. 29.CreditCredit...Associated PressThank you for your patience while we verify access. If you are in Reader mode please exit and log into your Times account, or subscribe for all of The Times.Thank you for your patience while we verify access.Already a subscriber? Log in.Want all of The Times? Subscribe.AdvertisementSKIP ADVERTISEMENT",
